<TEXT>
<P>
A dispute between Jerry Reynolds, coach of the Sacramento Kings, and guard 
Derek Smith could come to a head today with the end of Smith's six-day 
suspension. 
</P>
<P>
According to the Sacramento Bee, negotiations to buy out Smith's contract have 
deadlocked, with Reynolds threatening to quit if Smith rejoins the team. Smith 
says he will report to practice unless he's waived. 
</P>
<P>
Smith's agent, Ron Grinker, said the 27-year-old guard, acquired by the Kings 
in a 1986 trade with the Clippers, intends to file a defamation suit against 
the Kings if the club refuses either to allow him back or waive him. 
</P>
<P>
Gregg Lukenbill, the Kings' managing general partner, said the team will stand 
behind Reynolds and end its three-year association with Smith, who has been on 
reserve status since December. 
</P>
<P>
Reynolds suspended Smith Jan. 30 after a disagreement during a team meeting. 
</P>
